(55, 3, '2013-01-27 17:59:34', '2013-01-27 17:59:34', 'If you''re an advocate or friend trying to help someone who believes they''re being cyberstalked, work through a checklist with them to find out what''s happening. Keep in mind that, until you can get away from the abuser''s surveillance, communications can put you both at risk. If you work for an organization that helps other survivors, things like GPS monitoring that give away shelter locations can put everyone in danger.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nIn general, it is important to understand that devices may be used as microphones to provide surveillance. They may have software remotely loaded to enable surveillance of phone calls. Or, they may have software or hardware attached or installed that allows abusers to overhear all conversations held within earshot of a phone, regardless or whether the owner is using it as a phone and regardless of whether the phone is turned on or off, or even whether or not the batteries are removed. The first rule is, make sure the cellphone is well away from you and out of earshot. Talk to victims on land lines only.\r\n\r\nIf you are providing help, the first question to ask is, “Where’s your cellphone and where are your mobile devices?” Be sure they are removed from they are and out of earshot before proceeding to provide help. Keep them 100 feet away from you, in another room, or have the victim leave it at home or in the car.\r\n\r\nLand lines can be tapped by a non-government employee abuser, but it is significantly harder than tapping a cellphone. Government agencies can more easily tap land lines. For non-government employees, cellphones are easier. It is therefore almost always preferable to talk on land lines.\r\n\r\nAs a general rule, try to conduct a diversionary conversation with the victim intended to confuse tapper and lull them into a sense of security that they are not detected. Otherwise, they can grow enraged, putting the victim''s life in danger, or take countermeasures which will defeat the target’s measures to avoid them overhearing. Explain this to the victim only when you are sure you are talking securely. When working with a client or anyone whose phone may be tapped, prevent your own contact information from coming into the scope of the tapper.\r\n\r\n<em>If a Victim Calls You:</em>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>At the very beginning of the call: do not discuss at that moment whether or not the line is tapped</li>\r\n	<li>If the partner or person on the call brings it up, redirect away from this topic as the tapper will overhear</li>\r\n	<li>Always ask the client or person on the call at very beginning of conversation what phone they are using</li>\r\n	<li>If they are not on a land line, and you cannot forensically examine their telecommunications device, you must assume the call is tapped. Whether it is or not is not possible to determine without forensic examination of the (cellphone) device</li>\r\n	<li>Make arrangements for them to call you back from a land line, preferably not in their own house, preferably from a secure location</li>\r\n	<li>Terminate the call as soon as possible. That call is over.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nOnce they call you back from a land line:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Follow steps 1-5 above at start</li>\r\n	<li>Once you are sure they are on a land line, ask where their cellphone is at that moment. For the call to be secure, it must either have the batteries removed or be out of earshot. To remove the batteries on an iPhone, the victim will need a tiny screwdriver, so this may not be immediately feasible. To make sure the phone is out of earshot, it should be in the client’s car or other room away from victim with door closed. A better option as they can pretend they "forgot" it at home.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAfter the client secures the call through the above steps, you can proceed to communicate. Be aware that email communication with them may likely be compromised. They are likely tracked through GPS as well. That means their cellphone sitting outside in their car is informing the tapper of their physical location while calling you.', 'Can I Help?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'can-i-help', '', '', '2013-01-27 17:59:34', '2013-01-27 17:59:34', '', 0, 'http://www.fuerza.is/?page_id=55', 0, 'page', '', 0),
